# Go base repository pattern

## Rule
Mongo repositories embed `mongo.BaseRepository[T]`; MySQL repositories embed `mysql.BaseRepository[T]`. Custom queries go on the repository type; the base handles CRUD, filter translation, and tenant-aware DB handle resolution.

## Why
Every fb-rates-go repository follows this pattern per `coding-guidelines.md`. Base-repository factoring keeps tenant-aware Mongo handle resolution in exactly one place and ensures index definitions travel with the collection type.

## Constraints
- One repository per collection / table.
- Collection / table name is a constant on the repository, not inline strings.
- Indexes declared via the base-repository `Indexes()` method so creation runs at startup.
- Tenant-aware Mongo handle resolution (`TenantMongoManager`) is the base repo's responsibility — a new repo does not re-invent it.
- Aggregation pipelines live in dedicated helper methods, never inlined in services.

## Examples

### Good
```go
type FreightRateRepo struct { *mongo.BaseRepository[models.FreightRate] }

func New(mgr *tenant.MongoManager) *FreightRateRepo {
    return &FreightRateRepo{
        BaseRepository: mongo.NewBase[models.FreightRate](mgr, "tariff_freight_rates"),
    }
}
```

### Bad
```go
// Raw collection access in a service method
col := client.Database(name).Collection("tariff_freight_rates")
col.Find(ctx, bson.M{"vendorId": v})
```

